{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/nine-postgres-concepts-to-simplify-your-life-a0aa8c9bd87d", "time": 1682995665.025412, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/nine-postgres-concepts-to-simplify-your-life-a0aa8c9bd87d/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Nine Postgres concepts to simplify your life \ud83d\udc18 | by Varun Chitale | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Nine Postgres concepts to simplify your life \ud83d\udc18", "description": "It is simply easier to query textual corpus and get n-grams right off the bat than using another scripting language. The resulting data can be stored for multiple purposes, including but not limited\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/implementing-auto-complete-with-postgres-and-python-e03d34824079", "anchor_text": "article", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "https://malisper.me/table-of-contents/", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 16}], "all_paragraphs": ["It is simply easier to query textual corpus and get n-grams right off the bat\u00a0than\u00a0using\u00a0another\u00a0scripting\u00a0language. The resulting data can be stored for multiple purposes, including but not limited to: key phrase identification, auto-complete prompts, auto-correct prompts. This set can also find its use in creating word and phrase vectors using contextual word2vec models.", "Here, <ordered record set of words> is a record set (obtained either directly or by some manipulations) of words in the order that they appear. It looks like this:", "The following query works beautifully for delete duplicates from a table considering multiple constraints. Here, all rows where column var1 and column var2 are identical are considered and a single copy is retained, where as the rest are deleted.", "Often times, updating row values in a table results in conflicts with existing rows. Some rogue entries prevent a simple straightforward update query from running till the end. To counter this, a hacky procedure to update the table row-wise, ignoring entries conflicting with constraints, works charmingly. You may choose to log these rows for further processing in the exception handling.", "Another way to deal with this is to remove the conflicting constraint, update the table normally, take care of the conflicting rows(e.g remove duplicates) and re-add the constraint. This is not a recommended method.", "Constraints are sometimes essential when copying a table and can be included so:", "It is easy to be in a situation where multiple processes hold locks over common relations, resulting in deadlock situations. Stale queries or dropped connections are obsolete and can be queried so:", "Blocking and/or blocked statements can can be terminated using the following query:", "It is easy to forget that JSON(/B) and their arrays can be queried just like you would in a scripting language. Consider the following jsonb structure as a cell in a relation:", "All of the following queries are possible:", "I would recommend reading this blog article before you take on the searching task:", "In another article, I delineate the basic steps that go into extraction of noun chunks, storing these in the dB, querying them and ranking the results. This article searches a data point based on the noun-chunk phrases it contains. This can be extended to full text search!", "Aggregation operators like grouping return a single grouped row for every grouped element. In order to get multiple rows per group, the following query works wonders.", "I have found the following three concepts to be of immense value in everyday querying.", "A little known feature. From the docs:", "To use autocomplete, begin typing your query; when you would like the Query editor to suggest object names or commands that might be next in your query, press the Control+Space key combination. For example, type \u201c*SELECT * FROM* \u201d (without quotes, but with a trailing space), and then press the Control+Space key combination to select from a popup menu of autocomplete options.", "A great blog that I enjoy reading can be found here.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fa0aa8c9bd87d&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fnine-postgres-concepts-to-simplify-your-life-a0aa8c9bd87d&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fnine-postgres-concepts-to-simplify-your-life-a0aa8c9bd87d&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fnine-postgres-concepts-to-simplify-your-life-a0aa8c9bd87d&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fnine-postgres-concepts-to-simplify-your-life-a0aa8c9bd87d&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign